SIMPLE: ouster
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ouster
<hw>Oust"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. fr. the OF.
infin. <ets>oster</ets>, used substantively. See <er>Oust</er>.]</ety>
<def>A putting out of possession; dispossession; disseizin; -- of a
person.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Ouster</qex> of the freehold is effected by abatement,
intrusion, disseizin, discontinuance, or deforcement.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Expulsion; ejection; <as>as, his misbehavior caused
his <ex>ouster</ex> from the party</as>; -- of a person, from a place or
group.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ouster le main</b></col>. <ety>[<ets>Ouster</ets> + F.
<ets>la main</ets> the hand, L. <ets>manus</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Law)</fld> <cd>A delivery of lands out of the hands of a guardian,
or out of the king's hands, or a judgement given for that purpose.</cd>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>ousting</ent>⟦br⟧
